<br>
Three newts, one firebelly, one oregon, and one spring. We originally got the firebelly for my husband, because he thought it was cute. After a couple of days it kinda grew on me too, and we got the oregon because I wanted one too... but if we'd have gotten another firebelly we wouldn't have been able to tell them apart hehe. Then like 6 or 7 months later we got the spring newt because I saw it at the petstore and thought it was adorable.<br>
<br>
For those who don't know... firebelly newts are the black ones with the red splotchy tummies and oregon newts are a pretty chocolate brown with solid yellow tummies. Spring newts are a pretty leaf green with orange and yellow speckles and stripes on top and white or lighter green tummies.<br>
<br>
Fortunately my newts got along and we didn't have a problem with them, not even when we added the spring newt, who at the time was about an inch to an inch and a half long while the firebelly was 4&quot; and the oregon was a whopping 6&quot; from nose to tailtip. This could have been because I am &quot;lazy&quot; when it came to feeding them... mine would NOT take dried/dead food, of any sort, and raising bloodworms and tubifex worms wasn't something I really cared for the idea of lol... so what did they eat?<br>
<br>
Feeder guppies. Live ones.<br>
<br>
I did have a kind of weird practice tho -- I would buy the tank 25 guppies every other week. Any guppy that survived (and there were plants and rocks and such, I like my pets to have as natural an enviroment as possible... and IMO, if you have to feed live food, give it the same &quot;chance&quot; it would have in the wild...) the full 14 days was carefully pulled out of the newt tank and moved into a nice feeder guppy retirement home lol -- I figured they deserved it.<br>
<br>
Lets see, what else...<br>
<br>
Well, there was a series of rats. My first rat was Ardwede (large black male with a white tummy stripe). He was named after my first boyfriend, name turned inside out and backwards. Bonus points for anyone except Tedi and Fadien who can guess (Tedi knows, and Fadien will just ask her lol). I used to carry him (the pet rat, not the boyfriend... who was a different kind of rat...) around on my shoulders wherever I went. This got some interesting looks in the McDonald's drive through, considering I lived just outside Chicago at the time... heh.<br>
<br>
My next rat was named Danae, after a character in a book. She was sweet, but kind of &quot;simple&quot;. Not much personality the poor little girl... she was a grey and white &quot;hooded&quot; rat, meaning she had a grey head, and a gray stripe (broken up a little) down her backbone and was otherwise white.<br>
<br>
Next came Fenrus McRat -- she was named after a rat familiar in an old computer game. Also black with the white tummy. She got the surname McRat because she was a &quot;rescue&quot; rodent -- My sister (not Tedi, another one... or was it Tedi... hmm.) said a friend of hers had a rat and his room-mate was abusing it and would I please rescue it? Of course I said yes... but the guy didn't have a box and she wasn't shoulder trained... and I had to walk home... well, what to do? I picked up a McDonald's bag off his trailer floor and carried her in that LOL. She was a sweetheart but SUCH the little rascal! She's the one who taught my non-rodent hubby why you never, EVER leave your dress shirt on top of a rat cage... heh.<br>
<br>
The next two rats were Jondalar and Ranec, a white male and a black male. They got along about as well as thier namesakes, sadly, and had to be caged separately... until one night... they BOTH managed to escape captivity! &lt;gasp&gt; The next morning I found them happily curled up together asleep on a bookshelf. They never DID learn to get along when caged... but I learned that these two didn't NEED a cage. I just gave them free run of my workroom (no cats allowed without direct supervision zone, it's where I kept my rodents and bred my shyer strains of fish). They loved waiting until I was painting a model horse and then run up my legs lol... ruined SO many models that way!<br>
<br>
After those two was a ratless period for a while, until I saw the cutest little grey rat at a pet store... and she was TINY... in a cage with 4 full grown males... umm, not good. I &quot;requested&quot; that they house her appropriately. Then I made the mistake of offering to hold her while they set up a new cage.<br>
<br>
Well, they didn't need a second cage, and Mote found her way home. Named after a rat in a book, she was tiny and grey just like the one in the book.<br>
<br>
Later, I discovered that while working two jobs was needed, I just didn't have TIME for her to get the attention she needed to be a single rat... and while pondering what to do about it, I made the mistake of going to another petstore to buy her a guilt offering of yogurt drops.<br>
<br>
Impulse followed me home heh. She was a darker blue/grey color with a white tummy splash.<br>
<br>
Unfortunately, they had to be given to a friend when I was unceremoniously forced to move to icky icky San Diego CA earlier this year. Ick.<br>
<br>
Thats it for the ratlings... what else... well, numerous hamsters. Most notable was &quot;My Fuzzy Valentine&quot; who was never called by her right name. Most of the time we just called her Fuzzy. Until one halloween...<br>
<br>
See, Fuzzy was a very LARGE hamster, even for a teddybear. And the petstore was holding a costume contest. I remembered an old D&amp;D monster (Spacehammer) called a &quot;S.P.A.M&quot; -- otherwise known as a Giant Space Hamster.<br>
<br>
This of course got my creative juices flowing, and Fuzzy was soon decked out with a cape made of felt, attached to a pipe cleaner collar with little antenna lol. Feeling that this wasn't enough, I then bought a mini-pumpkin and carved out a spaceship and put her in it. She was adorable hehe, and very good natured about sitting in her pumpkin and wearing her cape as long as I remembered to give her the occasional sunflower seed!<br>
<br>
What else... well, I've had mice of course. At one point over 300 of them living in my parent's basement heh. Gerbils by the dozen, they're SO fun to watch. One pair lived on my desk and I'd let them run around while I was writing. They made it into a story I wrote as a pair of not-quite familiars. Rabbits, almost all Dutch except for one big old lop. Guinea pigs (cavies), which are probably my favorite rodent... they're so cute it's scary. A finch... shoulda got more, I think Honey was lonely.<br>
<br>
Funny story about Honey... when I bought him, I followed all the advice for getting him from the box to the cage -- turned off the lights in the room so he wouldn't fly the wrong way etc. But I forgot to turn off the closet light! And there was JUST enough gap that Honey didn't go in the cage... he went into the closet.<br>
<br>
Well, I had something like 4 cats at the time... and I was scared that my pretty TINY new pet would get eaten... and I couldn't catch him no matter HOW I tried!<br>
<br>
What to do what to do!<br>
<br>
Then, a brainstorm! Get Tedi! Tedi will help me catch him!<br>
<br>
So off I go to Tedi's house... but she wasn't home. Then I remembered her mentioning she was going to go watch a friend play pool... but I couldn't remember the name of the bar. Well, about 2 hours and 20 bars later... there she was!<br>
<br>
By this time I was really worried... I'd closed the doors, but my engagement kitten was a REALLY intelligent cat... and I knew she knew how to get the bedroom door open...<br>
<br>
Next thing poor Tedi knew, I was clinging on her talking about a mile a minute... &quot;Honey got loose and I can't catch her and the cats are gonna eat her and I can't catch her and I need help because I can't catch her!!!!&quot; (I didn't learn Honey was a male until much later, when he started singing in the mornings... females don't sing in that species very well, and he was a virtuoso!)<br>
<br>
Well, she followed me home expecting I needed help with a rodent... heh... she was a little surprised at being called to help recapture a very small rather scared finch heh.<br>
<br>
Another interesting pet was a tortoise. I know I know, don't take wild animals home... but he was sitting right in the road, so I got out to move him to the side. This was when I discovered the poor fellow only had three legs 8( So he got put in the truck instead so I could ask the wisest person I knew (my father) what I should do? Dad decided to keep him heh... named him Churchy Le Femme... Churchy was a character. Loved fruits veggies, and CRICKETS! My goodness that tortoise could go through crickets like you wouldn't believe.<br>
<br>
One time, I had Churchy outside getting some sun, because I'd read when I got control of him that tortoises needed natural sunlight even if they had UV lamps. A neighbors cat (and this cat was mean, even attacked people sometimes) came charging at him. Churchy didn't even bother pulling into his shell... just snapped right out and latched on that cats nose! hehe... the neighbor came screeching from her patio to rescue her cat. I didn't think much of it until the apartment manager showed up a few hours later saying the neighbor claimed I was harboring a &quot;vicious swift moving predator&quot; that had attacked her cat. He started to nicely tell me I would have to get rid of whatever it was (she hadn't told him you see). I asked him if he wanted to meet the &quot;predator&quot;... he looked worried, assuming it was a dog or something I guess, but said yes.<br>
<br>
I came back with a three legged tortoise.<br>
<br>
He didn't believe this is what had attacked her cat, until she (who was leaning over the wall between our patios) said &quot;That's IT! That's what bit my poor little cat! Make her get rid of it!!!!&quot;<br>
<br>
I think they could hear him laughing for miles heh...<br>
<br>
&lt;looks at the novel she's written&gt;<br>
<br>
